UNDIAGNOSED DEATHS, BOVINE - MYANMAR: (RAKHINE) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 26 Sep 2018 13:53 MMT
Source: Eleven Myanmar [edited]
http://www.elevenmyanmar.com/local/15199


Hundreds of cattle in Minpya Township upper Pan Myaung Gyi creek in Rakhine state has reportedly died from an unidentified disease during this month [September 2018], according to locals.

Farmers in the region usually sent their cattle, after ploughing season, to the nearby hills and mountains for pasturing. The owners will go up to the hills to check on their cattle once a week. On one of their routine checks, the owners found many dead cattle spread across the area. Some cattle found dead have already started to decay. After inspecting the dead carcasses, no external wounds were found. Locals have assumed that the cattle had died from unidentified disease.

"In our Oo Pyin Taung village, 60 cattle have died. We don't know why our cattle were dying. Our animals were put out to pasture to a place 20 miles [about 32 km] distant from our village which is called Mago creek. Most of the dead animals were large sized cattle. We found that the throats of the animals were swollen. Our villagers hope that government departments will investigate the cause of death as soon as possible. Cattle owners are worried about more of their cattle dying. We couldn't say for sure how many exactly had died because there are no data collected for other villages. I lost 11 cattle," said [a farmer] from Oo Pyin Taung village.

At present, no medical checks for the cattle have been made, increasing the anxiety of cattle owners. An animal is worth Ks 900 000 to 1 000 000 (equivalent of about USD 562 to 625).

[Byline: Than Hlaing]

