[For the location of Minpya (Minbya) in Rakhine state, in the westernmost part of Myanmar, see map at https://goo.gl/maps/vuGhfFbq9Fx.

The media report above provides a few pieces of information which are of relevance to differential diagnosis:
1. The death of a considerable number of cattle took place within a week since the previous weekly visit of animal owners.
2. The affected cattle were, mainly, "large sized cattle".
3. The (only) external lesion which was observed by the owners was "swollen throats".
4. No clinical signs were seen (or reported??), probably indicative of the acuteness of the condition.

Applying Cornell university's "Consultant" search machine (Diagnostic Support System for Veterinary Medicine; http://consultant.vet.cornell.edu/), using the 2 signs "Neck swelling, mass cervical region" and "Sudden death, found dead" in bovines, 28 diagnoses, infectious and non-infectious, were suggested. Among the more acute infectious diseases, anthrax and clostridial diseases (such as, malignant edema, blackleg, gas gangrene) deserve particular attention.

Earlier in 2018, human cases of anthrax were reported from Myanmar; see Mod.MHJ's commentary in 20180525.5819426.

Information on any findings, if they become available, will be appreciated. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Myanmar: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6061973,6638]
